<div id="review_4288003499" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4288003499" />
    <a title="Mikey B." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1484029-mikey-b"><img alt="Mikey B." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1641475883p2/1484029.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4288003499?book_show_action=true">Oct 14, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mikey B." class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mikey B." href="/user/show/1484029-mikey-b">Mikey B.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780307277732" href="/book/show/2898552-the-siege-of-mecca">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1484029-mikey-b?shelf=islam">islam</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1484029-mikey-b?shelf=saudi-arabia">saudi-arabia</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1484029-mikey-b?shelf=journalism">journalism</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1484029-mikey-b?shelf=middle-east">middle-east</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1484029-mikey-b?shelf=20th-century-history">20th-century-history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1484029-mikey-b?shelf=united-states">united-states</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4288003499" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15119289794431511650">Winston Churchill once said (I paraphrase) “History is several things on the move at the same time”. This fine book by Yaroslav Trofimov illustrates this.<br/><br/>In November 1979 hundreds (the exact number will never be known) of Islamist fundamentalists made a violent siege of Islam’s holiest shrine in Mecca. They were protesting the sell-out of the ruling Saudi families to the West – that they had abandoned the strictures of Islam and the teachings of the Quran. The fundamentalists wanted to return to</span>
  <span id="freeText15119289794431511650" style="display:none">Winston Churchill once said (I paraphrase) “History is several things on the move at the same time”. This fine book by Yaroslav Trofimov illustrates this.<br /><br />In November 1979 hundreds (the exact number will never be known) of Islamist fundamentalists made a violent siege of Islam’s holiest shrine in Mecca. They were protesting the sell-out of the ruling Saudi families to the West – that they had abandoned the strictures of Islam and the teachings of the Quran. The fundamentalists wanted to return to what they claimed was the true meaning of Islam – namely restrict the role of woman, no music, no television… They were influenced by the Wahhabi religious fundamentalists of Saudi Arabia. The Wahhabis and the ruling Saudi oligarchs play a dangerous game together. Saudi Arabia is a country cut-off from the rest of the world (although, today, that is slowly changing) and laden with toxic contradictions.<br /><br />Page 232 (my book)<br /><br /><i>Nobody in Riyadh wanted Saudi allies – or enemies – to know just how deep the rot went in Saudi Arabia. This again would be the pattern in future Saudi anti-terror investigations.</i><br /><br />At the initial stages of the siege, it was thought that the rebels were Shite Iranians - the Ayatollah Khomeini had just seized power in Iran and had laid siege to the U.S. embassy in Teheran and held hostages. Then it was thought that it was a U.S. Zionist plot. This crazy conspiracy theory spread like wildfire in many Muslim countries - like Pakistan, Libya, and even to the Muslim community in India. In Islamabad the U.S. embassy was burnt to the ground with the staff fleeing for their lives.<br /><br />The first attempts by the Saudi Army, National Guard, and police to rid the Holy Shrine of the rebels failed miserably with many deaths. In addition, there were Shite uprisings in the east of Saudi Arabia where the bulk of the oil fields and American workers are located. This was thought to have been started by Iran. These uprisings were ruthlessly suppressed.<br /><br />Also, the Soviets were becoming more and more preoccupied with Afghanistan. This was starting to set off alarm bells in many Muslim countries as well as the West.<br /><br />Finally, with the help of Americans and French chemical weapons (CB spraying devices) after two weeks the Saudis ended the siege. It is estimated that over one thousand soldiers, rebels, and civilians were killed. Due to the Saudis withholding data and obfuscating throughout, the exact number will never be known.<br /><br />As the author well describes it, this was an intense time in world history and the repercussions are brilliantly outlined. <br /><br />The religious fundamentalists who laid siege were the pre-cursors of Al-Qaeda. Their leader Jahayman wrote a one-hundred-page tract that spread to many Muslim countries, and influenced Khalid Islambouli, who in October/1981 assassinated Egyptian President Anwar Sadat. Also influenced was Osama Bin Laden.<br /><br />After this the Saudi royal family encouraged the Wahhabi fundamentalists to export their religious zealotry to other countries – one was Afghanistan. They provided millions of dollars in support of this proselytization - setting up mosques across the globe with propagandistic religious texts, plus sending both men and weapons to Afghanistan.<br /><br />This book gives us an insightful perspective on the inner operations of Saudi Arabia. It is not pretty, not transparent, and far from humanitarian.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15119289794431511650" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


