<div id="review_13319128" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/13319128" />
    <a title="C." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/36341-c"><img alt="C." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1621683273p2/36341.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/13319128?book_show_action=true">Jan 23, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="C." class="user" itemprop="url" name="C." href="/user/show/36341-c">C.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/36341-c?shelf=abandoned">abandoned</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/36341-c?shelf=political">political</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer13319128" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4680103484193913630">One of the episodes from &quot;The Looming Tower&quot; that struck me the most was the 1979 capture of the Grand Mosque in Mecca. In the midst of the hajj, when the Mosque was filled with worshipers from around the globe, a group of terrorists took the entire assembly hostage. The resulting siege lasted weeks and ended with a blood-bath of Saudi troops, hostages, and terrorists. Before I was even done with the &quot;The Looming Tower&quot; I started looking for a book about the incident.<br/><br/>There are a few reasons I de</span>
  <span id="freeText4680103484193913630" style="display:none">One of the episodes from "The Looming Tower" that struck me the most was the 1979 capture of the Grand Mosque in Mecca. In the midst of the hajj, when the Mosque was filled with worshipers from around the globe, a group of terrorists took the entire assembly hostage. The resulting siege lasted weeks and ended with a blood-bath of Saudi troops, hostages, and terrorists. Before I was even done with the "The Looming Tower" I started looking for a book about the incident.<br /><br />There are a few reasons I decided to stop reading this book:<br /><br />1. Melodramatic-prose. What I loved about "The Looming Tower" is that the author let the people and events speak for themselves. Terrorism is inherently dramatic and horrific -- cluttering it up with excessive adjectives cheapens things and smacks of sensationalism. When it comes to Islam, however, it becomes downright dangerous, as lingering on wild-eyes, tattered beards, and dusty robes plays unnecessarily into orientalist stereotypes.<br /><br />2. Pro Western backed state bias. Obviously the terrorists are "bad," I'm not saying that I support their actions. What made "The Looming Tower" so powerful, however, is that he let you come to that (obvious) conclusion on your own. He never went out of his way to make the leaders of Al-Jihad or the Islamic Brotherhood seem crazy or extreme -- he merely showed you what they did, gave you their words and how other Muslims reacted to them. The problem with the good/bad dichotomy that "Siege of Mecca" falls into is that it ignores the vast complexity of the issue, including the many legitimate complains that radical Islamic groups have. Failing to address that does nothing to advance dialogue or solve problems. The states they were revolting against were usually oppressive, horrible governments backed by US dollars. Which leads to<br /><br />3. A very conservative slant to geopolitics and history. Carter was a bungling idiot, we should have staunchly backed the Iranian shah, free-market oil is good. The entire Nation of Islam is casually dismissed as a mix of "armed radicalism and black racism," which does a huge disservice to the group. There are many things wrong with the Nation of Islam, but like he often does in this book, instead of addressing the complexities, the author boils it down to one biased sound-byte.<br /><br />I'd still love to read about these events, but this isn't the book I need.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4680103484193913630" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


