<div id="review_404180271" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/404180271" />
    <a title="Amar Pai" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/86362-amar-pai"><img alt="Amar Pai" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1363673390p2/86362.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/404180271?book_show_action=true">Aug 30, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Amar Pai" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Amar Pai" href="/user/show/86362-amar-pai">Amar Pai</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer404180271" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10940369679234354714">This was a really interesting book. A lot of it was news to me. I learned a lot about Saudi Arabia, and how it got to be the crazy place it is today. It always baffled me that Iran got counted in the &quot;Axis of Evil&quot; but Saudi Arabia didn&apos;t. I actually agree that the totalitarian govts of Iran, North Korea and Syria are &quot;evil&quot; (to the extent that word means anything, which isn&apos;t much) but how is Saudi Arabia not also evil?<br/><br/>The author definitely uses polemical language at times, and I was irritated </span>
  <span id="freeText10940369679234354714" style="display:none">This was a really interesting book. A lot of it was news to me. I learned a lot about Saudi Arabia, and how it got to be the crazy place it is today. It always baffled me that Iran got counted in the "Axis of Evil" but Saudi Arabia didn't. I actually agree that the totalitarian govts of Iran, North Korea and Syria are "evil" (to the extent that word means anything, which isn't much) but how is Saudi Arabia not also evil?<br /><br />The author definitely uses polemical language at times, and I was irritated with his point of view that Carter was naive &amp; foolish to have turned his back on the Shah of Iran. The Shah's SAVAK secret police were notorious torturers whom everyone in Iran despised! Carter was admirable in attempting to move away from supporting that regime. It's not like anybody had any idea that the Iranian revolution was going to happen, until it did. Revolutions are hard to predict, even though after the fact people always act like it was inevitable.<br /><br />But despite all that, Trofimov is a solid reporter-- his take on things struck me as pretty honest, he's got plenty of notes, and everything he says is backed by Google/wikipedia-- and more importantly, he's a good writer. He builds suspense and delivers the right amount of detail to keep you reading. And I really think the stuff in this book is fundamental if you want to understand a lot of what happened after the siege in 1979... I came into it skeptical about "the birth of al-Qaeda" subtitle, but <i>The Siege of Mecca</i> actually delivers the goods. Osama bin Laden and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Juhayman_al-Otaybi" rel="nofollow noopener">Juhayman al-Otaybi</a> were of one mind, and the line between latter and former is clear.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10940369679234354714" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


