  <span id="freeText7407425617922599460" style="display:none"> I was quite familiar with the Iranian hostage crisis in 1979 but had heard almost nothing about the take over of the Grand Mosque. Neither had I heard of the destruction of the American Embassy in Pakistan, and the attacks in Lybia, Turkey, and India. So I personally found it very interesting and informative.<br /> The way the author describes it, this was really a very pivotal event in the history of Islam, specifically Wahhabism, and American and Saudi relations. The way that he explained how the various religious beliefs, political agendas, and cultural differences all compounded the chaos, miscommunications, and tragedy really made all very clear and understandable. <br /> In an attempt to provide a full and accurate account of what really happened, the author has culled through the various and often conflicting accounts from all sides of this event. That means to present a coherent narrative he makes numerous judgment calls as to which account is believable. He is quite open about why he chooses one over the other and was quite convincing about the accuracy of his choices. </span>
