    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_999148362" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/999148362" />
    <a title="Urooj Janjua" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17121210-urooj-janjua"><img alt="Urooj Janjua" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1396278395p2/17121210.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/999148362?book_show_action=true">Jul 17, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Urooj Janjua" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Urooj Janjua" href="/user/show/17121210-urooj-janjua">Urooj Janjua</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer999148362" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10869261919549256589">I&apos;m not really writing a formal book review, just my thoughts on the book. This was a very well researched and well put together book. Usually, some of the books of this sort get so mired in facts and figures that they are a very dry and slow read - not so with this book. Not only does the author present the facts, but usually he doesn&apos;t give much credence to the &quot;claims&quot; and &quot;boasts&quot; of the people involved, doing his own sleuthing of facts as well. I think his work in Islamic countries, and the</span>
  <span id="freeText10869261919549256589" style="display:none">I'm not really writing a formal book review, just my thoughts on the book. This was a very well researched and well put together book. Usually, some of the books of this sort get so mired in facts and figures that they are a very dry and slow read - not so with this book. Not only does the author present the facts, but usually he doesn't give much credence to the "claims" and "boasts" of the people involved, doing his own sleuthing of facts as well. I think his work in Islamic countries, and the Arab world, has given him a very good insight into not only how the Arabs work (especially the Gulf Arabs), but also how political Islam plays a part in these countries. <br /><br />The most amusing thing, for me, is how while the Muslims try to cover this uprising up and pretend it never happened, especially those countries that are under heavy Saudi influence (there are people in my own country who look at you blankly when you talk about the attack on Ka'aba and think you're either lying or joking), not only does this "foreign and kaafir" (I use these terms ironically, not disparagingly) journalist uncover the shame, but he does it very tactfully and artfully, without missing any of the nuances involved. <br /><br />It is ironic that in a bid to secure their "kingship" (not kingdom, it never is about the kingdom and the people), the House of Saud not only cemented the "new takfiri" brand of Islam (whereby you justify murdering Muslims by pronouncing them infidels), something all the Salafi/Wahabi terrorists in my country adhere to and benefit by, by asking the local muftis and ulema to declare them infidels so that they could kill them easily and without any "religious backlash", but that in a bid to woo the local muftis, so that their reign does not end due to Juhayman and his Mahdi's takeover of the Ka'aba (as this showed their regime's incompetence), they actually ended up implementing all the archaic and bigoted laws that the terrorist group was demanding. Not only were women further pushed back into their homes, with jobs being taken away from them, and relegated to second or even third class citizens, but all the "modernisation" that King Faisal had introduced was rolled back as well. <br /><br />What I find further amusing, though nothing new to be honest, is how the House of Saud would do anything to keep their rule. Whether it is to reject the help of Jordan because of a matter of "ego" and not to look "weak" after having usurping the role of "Khadim Harimain Sharifain" from them, or to go around secretly making fake "converts" all the while blaming Iran for the involvement, it is clear that there are no depths the House of Saud will stoop to as long as they get to reign. <br /><br />I liked that the author mentioned how badly the Shi'a are treated in Saudi Arabia, and how they're always looked at with suspicion (the recent suicide bombings in which Saudi Shi'as were targetted are not an anomaly, it's just that it's harder for them to hide this kind of stuff now, thanks to technology). The plight of the Shi'a in Saudi should not be ignored, though, to be fair, usually the House of Saud is busy funding the terrorists abroad (in my country for instance) to have the "kaafir Shi'as" murdered and maimed. However, I feel the chickens have finally come home to roost, and it is Saudi itself that is becoming a hot mess of intolerance and bigotry, and for once they can't really hide it, despite jailing, flogging, and beheading dissidents. Hell, we even get to hear about the jailing, flogging, and beheading as well. <br /><br />To come back to the book, it gave a good account of the events that led up to and immediately followed the Siege of Ka'aba in 1979. If you want to know a bit about how the current "Islamist" terrorism was birthed, this is a good place to start. However, you'd have to read other books if you want to know more about Al-Qaeda and other such groups, as this can only be a "starter's guide" of sorts as it relates the event that actually got the ball rolling. </span>
  <a data-text-id="10869261919549256589" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


