        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2114825181" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12785892749917968902">This book describes a relatively underpublicized set of events in 1979--in which both a group of fundamentalist wahabi inspired Muslim took over the Grand Mosque in Mecca, and virtually the same time a rebellion by majority Shia believers in Eastern Saudi Arabia (esp Qatif) took place. These events, the response by the Saudi government, the false information and provocations by the Ayatollah Khomeini government in Iran, and the gathering response by the mujaheddin in Afghanistan against Soviet-o</span>
  <span id="freeText12785892749917968902" style="display:none">This book describes a relatively underpublicized set of events in 1979--in which both a group of fundamentalist wahabi inspired Muslim took over the Grand Mosque in Mecca, and virtually the same time a rebellion by majority Shia believers in Eastern Saudi Arabia (esp Qatif) took place. These events, the response by the Saudi government, the false information and provocations by the Ayatollah Khomeini government in Iran, and the gathering response by the mujaheddin in Afghanistan against Soviet-occupied Afghanistan all drew long shadows which which are very much in evidence today. The lack of understanding of how serious these events were by the American governments (Carter's government in particular seems to have been completely wrong-headed/incompetent, but Reagan's subsequent focus on combatting the Soviet Union at the cost of ignoring the global implications of how the US was portrayed by many leaders in the Islamic world during these events, esp in Pakistan, Iran and even the KSA), are a potent reminder of how complex dealing with the various strains of Islam are internationally. Wall Street Journal reporter Trofimov seems to have done a thorough job researching the various sides in the dramas covered in this book--which first appeared in 2007. Highly recommend this book to those interested in understanding the Middle East and especially the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia's present dealings with the US and west more generally, as well as the clear continuing tensions between Iran and the Kingdom.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12785892749917968902" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


