<div id="review_796713376" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/796713376" />
    <a title="Kevinkrisciunas" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18427438-kevinkrisciunas"><img alt="Kevinkrisciunas" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/796713376?book_show_action=true">Dec 21, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kevinkrisciunas" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kevinkrisciunas" href="/user/show/18427438-kevinkrisciunas">Kevinkrisciunas</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer796713376" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4954952049658886854">This book was given to me by a college student originally from Saudi Arabia. As one of the testimonials says, you will have a hard time putting it down once you start reading it. It tells the story of a takeover of the Great Mosque in Mecca during November, 1979. The world&apos;s attention was busy with the takeover of the US Embassy in Tehran. The episode covered here owed its occurrence to a group of mostly Saudi Sunni fanatics. The security forces of the Saudi government were unable to end the tak</span>
  <span id="freeText4954952049658886854" style="display:none">This book was given to me by a college student originally from Saudi Arabia. As one of the testimonials says, you will have a hard time putting it down once you start reading it. It tells the story of a takeover of the Great Mosque in Mecca during November, 1979. The world's attention was busy with the takeover of the US Embassy in Tehran. The episode covered here owed its occurrence to a group of mostly Saudi Sunni fanatics. The security forces of the Saudi government were unable to end the takeover. They finally had to bring in three top notch advisors from France, who made a list of material necessary to end the takeover of the mosque: armored personnel carriers, gas masks, and a particular kind of poison gas. Hundreds of pilgrims, soldiers, and terrorists died in the mayhem, which the Saudi government tried to hush up as fast as possible. Curiously, many of the top Saudi officials who were involved 35 years ago are still alive and powerful as of the time of the writing (2007). I highly recommend this book. While the individual chapters do not have titles, so many could be called "The plot thickens", because it just kept getting further and further out of hand. And events like this helped give birth to al Qaeda, b/c of the severe dislike of some Muslims to any Western presence in the mid-East and central Asia, be it Soviets, Americans, or Western Europeans. Just to give an example of the volatility of the situation, the suspicion that the Americans had something to do with the events in Meccas led to the destruction of the US Embassy in Islamabad, Pakistan - there the Pakistani army just stood by and watched as a riot-crazed mob attacked the embassy. Most of the embassy staff were in a safe vault, from which they eventually escaped, but only after many harrowing hours of uncertainty. You probably did not know that the construction of the underground areas of the Great Mosque were laid out by the head of Bin Laden Construction, the father of Osama bin Laden. The father provided the blueprints to the commandos trying to end the siege. Soon the son adopted many of the ideas of the leader of the terrorists and set out to rid Afghanistan of the Soviets. You know much of the rest. </span>
  <a data-text-id="4954952049658886854" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


