<div id="review_2040802160" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2040802160" />
    <a title="Kusaimamekirai" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/33921897-kusaimamekirai"><img alt="Kusaimamekirai" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1591523190p2/33921897.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2040802160?book_show_action=true">Jun 29, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kusaimamekirai" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kusaimamekirai" href="/user/show/33921897-kusaimamekirai">Kusaimamekirai</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2040802160" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15538620039134783273"> Nothing happens in a vacuum. <br/> Rather, tragedy seems to compound tragedy. <br/> There was the Saudis discovering oil at the beginning of the 20th century leading to the subsequent multinational presence in Saudi Arabia to exploit it. This led to immense wealth for the Saudi kings who often flaunted it in ways that upset devout Muslims, angry about foreigners in the holy land and their corrupt leaders. Which led to the seizure by these muslims in 1979 of the grand mosque at Mecca (the subject of this </span>
  <span id="freeText15538620039134783273" style="display:none"> Nothing happens in a vacuum. <br /> Rather, tragedy seems to compound tragedy. <br /> There was the Saudis discovering oil at the beginning of the 20th century leading to the subsequent multinational presence in Saudi Arabia to exploit it. This led to immense wealth for the Saudi kings who often flaunted it in ways that upset devout Muslims, angry about foreigners in the holy land and their corrupt leaders. Which led to the seizure by these muslims in 1979 of the grand mosque at Mecca (the subject of this book) to reclaim Islam from what they viewed as an illegitimate state. <br /> This led to a massive outpouring of violence from people who believed that the West was behind it. This violence, in Pakistan, Libya, Iran, Kuwait and others was directed primarily at American embassies, personnel and property. Which became the reason that the United States decided a massive military presence in the region was necessary. Which led to the first Gulf War which begat an Al Qaeda furious about the American presence, which begat the war in Iraq, which begat ISIS. <br /> Most of these events are relatively well known with the exception of the seizure of the grand mosque by a ragtag group of fundamentalists intent on installing a Mahdi to take over the Muslim world. Why this pivotal event in the aforementioned chain is never discussed is a mystery to me. Especially considering that the leader of this group to this day is cited as inspiration by jihadists (Bin Laden in particular was an admirer).<br /> This momentous event clearly set in motion a disturbing chain of events that continue to reverberate to this day. I only know that with each new page of this book I felt like so much that made little sense before became a little clearer. There is so much fascinating and important information here that I highly recommend this book to anyone who wants to get a better understanding about where we are today.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15538620039134783273" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


