<div id="review_3300378776" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3300378776" />
    <a title="Tanzeel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/113987521-tanzeel"><img alt="Tanzeel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1590266511p2/113987521.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3300378776?book_show_action=true">Apr 26, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tanzeel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tanzeel" href="/user/show/113987521-tanzeel">Tanzeel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/113987521-tanzeel?shelf=reviews">reviews</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3300378776" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16491873898989511398">As is a theme with my book reviews, I delve into inspiration behind the procurement of a book. A few days ago I was on twitter dot com and saw someone discussing the events that transpired in Mecca in 1979 - an event I was interested to learn more about - and they recommended reading “The Siege of Mecca”. Seeing this recommendation, I headed over to iBooks and purchased a copy to read on my iPad™️<br/><br/>The fact that I managed to read this book in two (2) days (unprecedented achievement by me during un</span>
  <span id="freeText16491873898989511398" style="display:none">As is a theme with my book reviews, I delve into inspiration behind the procurement of a book. A few days ago I was on twitter dot com and saw someone discussing the events that transpired in Mecca in 1979 - an event I was interested to learn more about - and they recommended reading “The Siege of Mecca”. Seeing this recommendation, I headed over to iBooks and purchased a copy to read on my iPad™️<br /><br />The fact that I managed to read this book in two (2) days (unprecedented achievement by me during unprecedented times) is a testament to Yaroslav Trofimov, who described the events in such depth that it felt I was present in Mecca at the time. <br /><br />On the dawn of the Islamic New Year 1400, Juhayman led a group of radicalised men on an assault of the Grand Mosque in Mecca. Juhayman, disappointed with how the House of Al Saud was transforming Saudi Arabia to appease the USA, captured the Grand Mosque which resulted in a bloody warfare on the grounds where muslims had gathered for pilgrimage a month prior. <br /><br />I had always wondered why an event of this magnitude, committed on Islam’s holiest site had never been spoken about much. The reasons for this became apparent as I read. Could it be the sheer arrogance and incompetence of the House of Saud? Or maybe that these events inspired a young Bin Laden? Find out when you read this book!</span>
  <a data-text-id="16491873898989511398" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


